  "Idea": "We propose a transformative framework for deep probabilistic Canonical Correlation Analysis (CCA) called \u0027Wasserstein-Refined Deep Probabilistic CCA\u0027 (WR-DPCCA), which reimagines variational inference as a structured optimal transport process over latent manifolds. While current methods rely on KL-divergence minimization and factorized posteriors, leading to posterior collapse and poor geometric alignment, WR-DPCCA introduces a novel two-tiered inference mechanism: (1) a global Optimal Transport (OT)-guided posterior refinement module for the shared latent variable z_s, and (2) local normalizing flow-based encoders for view-specific factors z_v. Unlike traditional amortized inference, our method treats the shared posterior q(z_s | x_1, x_2) not as a fixed output but as a dynamically updated distribution driven by Wasserstein gradient flows. Specifically, we formulate a transport loss based on the sliced Wasserstein distance between q(z_s) and the joint prior p(z_s), computed efficiently via random projections. This loss is integrated into the ELBO as a geometry-aware regularization term, encouraging the posterior to preserve topological structures and avoid mode collapse. To make this scalable, we employ implicit differentiation through the OT update step, enabling end-to-end training without explicit solver loops. The shared encoder is designed with partial invertibility to facilitate residual correction steps akin to amortized MCMC, now guided by OT dynamics rather than mean-field assumptions. For view-specific latents, we retain expressive neural flows but couple them with a neural Gaussian copula to model inter-latent dependencies between z_s and z_v, ensuring global coherence. A new \u0027cross-view transport consistency\u0027 loss enforces that canonical correlations induce aligned transport directions across modalities, enhancing identifiability. This fusion of OT theory, deep generative modeling, and CCA geometry enables more faithful posterior approximations, especially in low-sample regimes and high-dimensional data. The model supports missing data imputation, cross-modal generation, and uncertainty quantification with calibrated confidence intervals. By shifting from static KL-based inference to dynamic transport-aware learning, WR-DPCCA establishes a new direction for Bayesian multi-view representation learning.",
  "Title": "Wasserstein-Refined Deep Probabilistic CCA: Dynamic Posterior Approximation via Optimal Transport and Copula-Enhanced Latent Flows",
  "Experiment": "The implementation will proceed in four phases: (1) Model Architecture Design: Construct a deep generative decoder with linear mixing of shared z_s and view-specific z_v factors, followed by modality-specific deep decoders (e.g., CNNs for images, Transformers for text). Implement a dual-path inference network: a shared encoder with residual invertible blocks for z_s, augmented with an OT refinement layer that applies one-step Wasserstein gradient update using sliced Wasserstein distance; and separate flow-based encoders for each view\u0027s z_v. Integrate a neural parametric Gaussian copula to model dependencies between z_s and z_v in the joint posterior. (2) Objective Function: Define a hybrid loss combining IWAE-style importance-weighted ELBO, sliced Wasserstein regularization on q(z_s), copula log-determinant terms, and a transport consistency loss that aligns the Jacobian of z_s updates across views. Use automatic differentiation through implicit layers to backpropagate through the OT update. (3) Training Pipeline: Implement in PyTorch using Sinkhorn iterations for approximate OT gradients during warm-up, then switch to sliced Wasserstein for efficiency. Train on synthetic datasets with known latent topology (e.g., toroidal or clustered z_s), then benchmark on real-world data: MIDI-image pairs (MUSIC), multi-lingual sentences (Multi30k), and single-cell multi-omics (scRNA-seq + scATAC-seq). Use AdamW with staged learning rates: first optimize flows, then jointly train with OT terms. (4) Evaluation: Assess performance via held-out log-likelihood (importance sampling), posterior calibration (reliability diagrams), disentanglement (DCI, MIG), imputation RMSE, and downstream classification F1. Compare against Deep Probabilistic CCA, JVAE, and VOT-VAE. Ideal outcomes include reduced posterior collapse, improved latent geometry preservation, higher imputation accuracy under missingness, and superior uncertainty quantification.",
